<div class="description">
    <h3>Description</h3>

    <div class="body">
        <p>In the Zend_View Docs at (Version 1.10):
<a href="http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/zend.view.introduction.html">http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/…</a></p>

<p>it says:
"encoding: indicate the character encoding to use with htmlentities(), htmlspecialchars(), and other operations. Defaults to ISO-8859-1 (latin1). May be set via setEncoding() or the encoding  option to the constructor. "</p>

<p>In the advisory at:
<a href="http://framework.zend.com/security/advisory/ZF2010-01">http://framework.zend.com/security/advisory/…</a></p>

<p>it says:
"The afore-mentioned [Zend_View] classes have been reworked to use a default character encoding of UTF-8...a decision was made to default to UTF-8 for the internal encoding mechanisms used by Zend_View. "</p>

<p>These two documents seem to be conflicting.</p>

<hr /><p>Although, looking into my Zend_View object (version 1.9.8) it appears that it does default to UTF-8 - so the Documentation for Zend View is more likely to be the wrong one.</p>

<pre class="highlight"><code> 
abstract class Zend_View_Abstract implements Zend_View_Interface
{
    ...

    /**
     * Encoding to use in escaping mechanisms; defaults to utf-8
     * @var string
     */
    private $_encoding = 'UTF-8';

    ...
</code></pre>

